import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

1. Description of the problem

We are given a set of nodes, each defined by its x and y coordinates and an associated cost. The task is to select exactly half of the nodes (rounded up if the number is odd) and construct a Hamiltonian cycle that visits each selected node exactly once and returns to the starting node. The objective is to minimize the total sum of both the path length (computed using rounded Euclidean distances between nodes) and the costs of the selected nodes.

2. Pseudocode of implemented algorithms

2.1. Data

Input:

  • $n$: total number of nodes
  • $nodes[i] = (x_i, y_i, cost_i)$ for $i \in [0, n-1]$: array with all nodes
  • $dist[i][j] = \text{round}\!\left(\sqrt{(x_i - x_j)^2 + (y_i - y_j)^2}\right)$: euclidean distance between i-th and j-th node
  • $k = \lceil n / 2 \rceil$: number of nodes to select

Output:

  • $route$: list of nodes forming a closed Hamiltonian cycle
  • $totalCost = \text{distance cost} + \text{node costs}$

2.2. Random solution

FUNCTION randomSolution()
    route  list of integers [0, 1, 2, ..., n-1]
    SHUFFLE(route)

    route  first targetCount elements of route

    route.APPEND(route[0])

    totalCost  computeTotalCost(route)

    RETURN Result(route, totalCost)
END FUNCTION

2.3. Nearest neighbours adding node at the end

FUNCTION nearestNeighborEnd(startIndex)
    n  number of nodes
    route  [startIndex]
    used[n]  array of FALSE values
    used[startIndex]  TRUE
    current  startIndex

    WHILE route.size < targetCount
        bestDist  infinity
        next  -1

        FOR i FROM 0 TO n-1
            IF used[i] = FALSE THEN
                d  distanceMatrix[current][i] + nodes[i].cost
                IF d < bestDist THEN
                    bestDist  d
                    next  i
                END IF
            END IF
        END FOR

        IF next = -1 THEN
            BREAK
        END IF

        route.APPEND(next)
        used[next]  TRUE
        current  next
    END WHILE

    route.APPEND(startIndex)

    totalCost  computeTotalCost(route)
    RETURN Result(route, totalCost)
END FUNCTION

2.4. Nearest neighbour adding node anywhere

FUNCTION nearestNeighborFlexible(startIndex)
    n  number of nodes
    route  [startIndex, startIndex]  
    used[n]  array of FALSE values
    used[startIndex]  TRUE

    WHILE countUsed(used) < targetCount
        bestIncrease  infinity
        bestNode  -1
        bestPos  -1

        FOR node FROM 0 TO n-1
            IF used[node] = FALSE THEN
                FOR pos FROM 0 TO route.size - 2
                    a  route[pos]
                    b  route[pos + 1]
                    increase  distanceMatrix[a][node]
                                + distanceMatrix[node][b]
                                - distanceMatrix[a][b]
                                + nodes[node].cost

                    IF increase < bestIncrease THEN
                        bestIncrease  increase
                        bestNode  node
                        bestPos  pos + 1
                    END IF
                END FOR
            END IF
        END FOR

        IF bestNode = -1 THEN
            BREAK
        END IF

        route.INSERT(bestPos, bestNode)
        used[bestNode]  TRUE
    END WHILE

    totalCost  computeTotalCost(route)
    RETURN Result(route, totalCost)
END FUNCTION

2.5. Greedy cycle

FUNCTION greedyCycle(startIndex)
    n  number of nodes
    numToSelect  ceil(n / 2)
    route  [startIndex]
    used[n]  array of FALSE values
    used[startIndex]  TRUE
    
    bestSecond  -1
    minObj  infinity

    FOR i FROM 0 TO n-1
        IF used[i] = FALSE THEN
            obj  2 * distanceMatrix[startIndex][i]
                   + nodes[startIndex].cost
                   + nodes[i].cost
            IF obj < minObj THEN
                minObj  obj
                bestSecond  i
            END IF
        END IF
    END FOR

    IF bestSecond = -1 THEN
        RETURN Result(route, 0)
    END IF

    route.APPEND(bestSecond)
    used[bestSecond]  TRUE

    WHILE route.size < numToSelect
        bestNode  -1
        bestPos  -1
        bestIncrease  infinity

        FOR i FROM 0 TO n-1
            IF used[i] = FALSE THEN
                FOR j FROM 0 TO route.size - 1
                    a  route[j]
                    b  route[(j + 1) MOD route.size]
                    increase  distanceMatrix[a][i]
                                + distanceMatrix[i][b]
                                - distanceMatrix[a][b]
                                + nodes[i].cost

                    IF increase < bestIncrease THEN
                        bestIncrease  increase
                        bestNode  i
                        bestPos  j + 1
                    END IF
                END FOR
            END IF
        END FOR

        IF bestNode = -1 THEN
            BREAK
        END IF

        route.INSERT(bestPos, bestNode)
        used[bestNode]  TRUE
    END WHILE

    totalCost  computeTotalCost(route)
    RETURN Result(route, totalCost)
END FUNCTION

In[124]:
def plot_tsp(tsp, solution, title):
    X = tsp['x'].loc[solution].values
    Y = tsp['y'].loc[solution].values
    costs = tsp['cost'].loc[solution].values

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.scatter(X, Y, s=costs, color='red', alpha=0.4, label='Data points')
    plt.scatter(X, Y, color='blue')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel('X')
    plt.ylabel('Y')

    plt.plot(X, Y, color='blue', linestyle='-', linewidth=2, label='Connecting line')

8. Conclusions

  1. Greedy cycle method and second variant of nearest neighbour produce equally good results
  2. Nearest neighbour heuristic, that allows adding node anywhere is generalization of Nearest neighbour heuristic, that allows adding node at the end, thus it can't be worse.
  3. Among above three, random solution produced worst solutions (as expected). However, if we would run the simulation for suitable amount of time it is possible that we would 'guess' some good ones, even better than produced by other methods
  4. Greedy cycle and second variant of nearest neighbour take most time to compute, first variant of nearest neighbour takes less amount of time and random solution takes the least amount of time. It is because random solution has time complexity of $O(n)$, first variant of nearest neighbour has time complexity of $O(n^2)$ and remaining ones have time complexity of $O(n^3)$. If our problem would be much much larger, we would probably have to take it into account, but for this lab we didn't have that problem.
